{"parse":{"title":"Apotropaic mark","pageid":52147324,"revid":833813400,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:332px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg/330px-Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg\" width=\"330\" height=\"215\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg/495px-Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg/660px-Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"906\" data-file-height=\"590\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Apotropaic_pentagram_at_Niemala.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Apotropaic marking on a farmhouse from Niemel\u00e4 Tenant Farm, now exhibited at <a href=\"/wiki/Seurasaari\" title=\"Seurasaari\">Seurasaari Open Air Museum</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Finland\" title=\"Finland\">Finland</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Apotropaic marks</b> are symbols or patterns scratched into the fabric of a building <a href=\"/wiki/Apotropaic_magic\" title=\"Apotropaic magic\">to keep witches out</a>. They are sometimes called witches' marks, a term also used to denote <a href=\"/wiki/Witches%27_mark\" title=\"Witches&#39; mark\">identifying marks once thought to be found on the bodies of witches</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Marks_on_buildings\">Marks on buildings</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Apotropaic_mark&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Marks on buildings\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Apotropaic marks (from Greek <i>apotrepein</i> \"to ward off\" from <i>apo-</i> \"away\" and <i>trepein</i> \"to turn\") are symbols or patterns scratched into the fabric of a building with the intention of keeping witches out through <a href=\"/wiki/Apotropaic_magic\" title=\"Apotropaic magic\">apotropaic magic</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Evil was thought to be held at bay through a wide variety of apotropaic objects such as <a href=\"/wiki/Amulet\" title=\"Amulet\">amulets</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Talisman\" title=\"Talisman\">talismans</a> against the <a href=\"/wiki/Evil_eye\" title=\"Evil eye\">evil eye</a>. Marks on buildings were one application of this type of belief.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Marks have been found at <a href=\"/wiki/Shakespeare%27s_Birthplace\" title=\"Shakespeare&#39;s Birthplace\">Shakespeare's Birthplace</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Stratford-upon-Avon\" title=\"Stratford-upon-Avon\">Stratford-upon-Avon</a>, at the <a href=\"/wiki/Tower_of_London\" title=\"Tower of London\">Tower of London</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and many churches, but little effort has been made to find them on secular buildings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The marks are most common near places where witches were thought to be able to enter, whether doors, windows or chimneys.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> For example, during works at <a href=\"/wiki/Knole_House\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Knole House\">Knole House</a> in 1609, oak beams beneath floors, particularly near fireplaces, were scorched and carved with scratched witch marks to prevent witches and demons from coming down the chimney.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  At the <a href=\"/wiki/Bradford-on-Avon_Tithe_Barn\" title=\"Bradford-on-Avon Tithe Barn\">Bradford-on-Avon Tithe Barn</a>, a <a href=\"/wiki/Overlapping_circles_grid\" title=\"Overlapping circles grid\">flower-like pattern of overlapping circles</a> is incised into a stone in the wall.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Similar marks of overlapping circles have been found on a window cill dated about 1616 at <a href=\"/wiki/Owlpen_Manor\" title=\"Owlpen Manor\">Owlpen Manor</a> in Gloucestershire.\n</p><p>Other types of mark include the intertwined letters V and M or a double V (for the protector, the <a href=\"/wiki/Virgin_Mary\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Virgin Mary\">Virgin Mary</a>, alias <i>Virgo Virginum</i>), and crisscrossing lines to confuse any spirits that might try to follow them.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Apotropaic_mark&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Taper_burn_mark\" title=\"Taper burn mark\">Taper burn mark</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Apotropaic_mark&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Kennedy2016-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy2016_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Kennedy, Maev (31 October 2016). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2016/oct/31/witches-marks-historic-england-evil-spirits\">\"Witches' marks: public asked to seek ancient scratchings in buildings\"</a>. The Guardian<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">31 October</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Witches%27+marks%3A+public+asked+to+seek+ancient+scratchings+in+buildings&amp;rft.pub=The+Guardian&amp;rft.date=2016-10-31&amp;rft.aulast=Kennedy&amp;rft.aufirst=Maev&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fculture%2F2016%2Foct%2F31%2Fwitches-marks-historic-england-evil-spirits&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Asuni, John. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://archaeologicalmuseum.jhu.edu/the-collection/object-stories/the-roman-house-at-hopkins/the-art-of-light/apotropaic-talisman-against-the-evil-eye/\">\"Apotropaic Talisman Against the \"Evil Eye<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">\"</span>\"</a>. Johns Hopkins Archaeological Museum<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">31 October</span> 2016</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Apotropaic+Talisman+Against+the+%E2%80%9CEvil+Eye%E2%80%9D&amp;rft.pub=Johns+Hopkins+Archaeological+Museum&amp;rft.aulast=Asuni&amp;rft.aufirst=John&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Farchaeologicalmuseum.jhu.edu%2Fthe-collection%2Fobject-stories%2Fthe-roman-house-at-hopkins%2Fthe-art-of-light%2Fapotropaic-talisman-against-the-evil-eye%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">\"Tower of London staff 'used magic to repel the forces of the Devil<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">'</span>\". <a href=\"/wiki/The_Independent\" title=\"The Independent\">The Independent</a>. 16 October 2015.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Tower+of+London+staff+%27used+magic+to+repel+the+forces+of+the+Devil%27&amp;rft.pub=The+Independent&amp;rft.date=2015-10-16&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"display:none;font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Missing or empty <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;url=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#cite_web_url\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>); </span><span style=\"display:none;font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\"><code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;access-date=</code> requires <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;url=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#accessdate_missing_url\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Wright, James (19 October 2015). \"<span style=\"padding-left:0.2em;\">\"</span>The Instruments of Darkness Tells us Truths\". Ritual Protection Marks and Witchcraft at Knole, Kent\". <a href=\"/wiki/Gresham_College\" title=\"Gresham College\">Gresham College</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=%22The+Instruments+of+Darkness+Tells+us+Truths%22.+Ritual+Protection+Marks+and+Witchcraft+at+Knole%2C+Kent&amp;rft.pub=Gresham+College&amp;rft.date=2015-10-19&amp;rft.aulast=Wright&amp;rft.aufirst=James&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> <span style=\"display:none;font-size:100%\" class=\"error citation-comment\">Missing or empty <code style=\"color:inherit; border:inherit; padding:inherit;\">&#124;url=</code> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:CS1_errors#cite_web_url\" title=\"Help:CS1 errors\">help</a>)</span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Kennedy-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Kennedy_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Kennedy, Maev (2014-11-05). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2014/nov/05/witch-marks-king-james-i-knole-sevenoaks-national-trust\">\"Witch marks fit for a king beguile archaeologists at Knole\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Guardian\" title=\"The Guardian\">The Guardian</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2014-11-05</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Guardian&amp;rft.atitle=Witch+marks+fit+for+a+king+beguile+archaeologists+at+Knole&amp;rft.date=2014-11-05&amp;rft.aulast=Kennedy&amp;rft.aufirst=Maev&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theguardian.com%2Fculture%2F2014%2Fnov%2F05%2Fwitch-marks-king-james-i-knole-sevenoaks-national-trust&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.lassco.co.uk/lassco-news/2013/10/29/here-be-witchcraft/\">\"Here Be Witchcraft\"</a>. Lassco. 29 October 2014<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">31 October</span> 2016</span>. <q>f you live in a timber-framed house dating back earlier than the eighteenth century look out for scratchings on the bressumer beam, sometimes only very lightly inscribed at the top corners of the fireplace, like the scratching of a cat. Look for a repeated \u201cW\u201d \u2013 thought to be a double \u201cV\u201d for \u201cVirgo Virginum\u201d. Look for daisy wheels \u2013 a circular device with petals, or runic symbols \u2013 a \u201cP\u201d incorporating a cross, or a \u201cW\u201d incorporating a \u201cP\u201d. Look for two verticals with a \u201cSaltire\u201d cross between them \u2013 a motif also much used on iron door latches and bolts and wrought iron firedogs (St Andrew was considered the best hex against witches particularly in Northern England and Scotland).</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Here+Be+Witchcraft&amp;rft.pub=Lassco&amp;rft.date=2014-10-29&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lassco.co.uk%2Flassco-news%2F2013%2F10%2F29%2Fhere-be-witchcraft%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AApotropaic+mark\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2147\nCached time: 20180914202553\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.116 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.145 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 411/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 13455/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 243/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 12/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 8390/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.047/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 2.68 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  121.055      1 -total\n 69.78%   84.475      1 Template:Reflist\n 43.90%   53.141      5 Template:Cite_web\n 24.47%   29.626      1 Template:Use_British_English\n 11.31%   13.688      1 Template:DMCA\n  8.99%   10.877      1 Template:Dated_maintenance_category\n  6.31%    7.640      1 Template:FULLROOTPAGENAME\n  5.49%    6.647      1 Template:Cite_news\n  3.78%    4.581      1 Template:Ns_has_subpages\n  2.27%    2.747      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:52147324-0!canonical and timestamp 20180914202553 and revision id 833813400\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Pages_using_web_citations_with_no_URL"},{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Pages_using_citations_with_accessdate_and_no_URL"},{"sortkey":"","hidden":"","*":"Use_British_English_from_October_2016"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Anthropology_of_religion"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Magic_(paranormal)"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Folklore"}],"links":[{"ns":14,"exists":"","*":"Category: